---
// v3.1 — The Lineage subsection. Twelve milestone timeline cards now
// link to per-milestone first-draft essays seeded from Phase 2
// substrate (lineage_12_milestones.md). Phase 3 cross-AI review and
// Phase 4 revision are still pending.
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import RoomLayout from '../../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';

const milestones = (await getCollection('court-lineage')).sort(
  (a, b) => a.data.order - b.data.order,
);
const slugify = (s: string) => s.replace(/^\d+-/, '');
---
<RoomLayout
  room="court"
  width="full"
  title="The Lineage"
  subtitle="Doctrinal evolution of trust law — from English equity to American school trust."
  sourceId="court-lineage"
>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none mt-8 prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <span class="eyebrow">Court Room · The Lineage</span>

    <aside class="preview-banner" role="note">
      <strong>First-draft preview.</strong> Fourteen milestone essays
      sketch the doctrinal arc from Magna Carta and the 1601 Statute of
      Charitable Uses through Asarco (1989) to the modern Uniform
      Trust Code. Phase 4 Wave 1 (v75) added pull-quotes and
      primary-source links to each waypoint and the methodological note
      below. ← <a href="/court/">Back to the Court Room lobby</a>.
    </aside>

    <aside class="methodological-note" role="note">
      <h2 style="margin: 0 0 0.45rem; font-size: 1.05rem;">Note on this lineage</h2>
      <p style="margin: 0;">
        This is a <em>conceptual lineage</em>, not a claim that each earlier
        source directly controls school-trust lands. The American
        school-trust regime drew on English equity tradition, took
        distinctively American shape in the <strong>Land Ordinance of
        May&nbsp;20,&nbsp;1785</strong> (the grant), was given its
        philosophical floor by the <strong>Northwest Ordinance of
        July&nbsp;13,&nbsp;1787</strong> (the declaration, <em>not</em> the
        grant), and continues to evolve under the Uniform Trust Code. A
        skeptical legal historian should read this timeline as orientation,
        not as a chain of binding precedent. Where one source binds
        another, the case-law citations make that explicit; where the
        influence is conceptual, the timeline names it as such.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      American school-trust law was not invented. It was inherited. The
      lineage runs from Magna Carta through five centuries of English
      Chancery practice, through the 1785 Land Ordinance and the 1787
      Northwest Ordinance, through the admission compact that every new
      state from Ohio onward signed with Congress, and into the modern
      Uniform Trust Code and Restatement (Third) of Trusts. Each milestone
      below is a hinge: the place where the doctrine took a new shape that
      every subsequent state inherited.
    </p>

    <ol class="lineage-list">
      {milestones.map((m) => (
        <li class="lineage-item">
          <div class="lineage-year">{m.data.year}</div>
          <div class="lineage-body">
            <h2 class="lineage-title">
              <a href={`/court/lineage/${slugify(m.slug)}/`}>{m.data.title}</a>
            </h2>
            {m.data.summary && (
              <p class="lineage-summary">{m.data.summary}</p>
            )}
            <p class="lineage-read">
              <a href={`/court/lineage/${slugify(m.slug)}/`}>Read the full essay →</a>
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ol>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--ink); opacity: 0.7;">
      First-draft preview. Long-form essays seeded from Phase 2 substrate;
      Phase 3 cross-AI review and Phase 4 revision still pending.
    </p>
  </article>
</RoomLayout>

<style>
  .preview-banner {
    border-left: 4px solid var(--old-gold, #B88A2E);
    background: rgba(184, 138, 46, 0.08);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
  .methodological-note {
    border: 1px solid #cbd5e1;
    border-left: 4px solid #1e3a5f;
    background: #f8fafc;
    padding: 0.85rem 1.1rem;
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
  .lineage-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding-left: 0;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
    border-left: 2px solid #cbd5e1;
  }
  .lineage-item {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 6rem 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem 1rem 1rem;
    position: relative;
  }
  .lineage-item::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: -7px;
    top: 1.2rem;
    width: 12px;
    height: 12px;
    background: var(--old-gold, #B88A2E);
    border: 2px solid #fff;
    border-radius: 50%;
  }
  .lineage-year {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #1e3a5f;
  }
  .lineage-body { min-width: 0; }
  .lineage-title {
    margin: 0 0 0.35rem;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
    color: #0f172a;
  }
  .lineage-title a {
    color: inherit;
    text-decoration: none;
    border-bottom: 1px dotted #94a3b8;
  }
  .lineage-title a:hover {
    color: #1d4ed8;
    border-bottom-color: #1d4ed8;
  }
  .lineage-summary {
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    color: #1f2937;
  }
  .lineage-read {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .lineage-item { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.35rem; }
  }
</style>
